          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "reported",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://theintercept.com/2021/04/14/cleveland-cuyahoga-shontel-brown-contracts-nina-turner/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " that Brown, who had pledged to recuse herself “as necessary” from contracts involving her partner, Mark Perkins, had used her position as Cuyahoga County Commissioner to help steer $17 million in contracts to Perk. Perk was founded with Perkins’ uncle but is now owned by the Cifani family, who have long-established business ties to the Perkins family and who have supported Brown’s campaigns for office.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Intercept",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " noted that in February 2017, weeks after approval of one of those contracts for $7 million, Perk hosted a fundraiser for Brown’s reelection campaign.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "According to emails provided to ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Daily Poster",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ", in April the ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Intercept",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "’s story was forwarded to the Ohio Attorney General’s office. The following month, an official in the attorney general’s office noted in an email that she discussed the matter with an attorney in the state auditor’s office. “We are both of the opinion that it makes sense for the Auditor’s office to review, and we also believe that this might end up being a case that is referred to Ethics Commission,” the official wrote.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Intercept",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "’s report was forwarded to the auditor’s office, and, according to a June 2 email from a representative of the office’s Special Investigations Unit, the matter has now been sent to the Ohio Ethics Commission, the state’s official public corruption watchdog, for review.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "“The recommendation by the Special Audit Task Force was to refer this matter to the Ohio Ethics Commission for its review and consideration,” noted the email. “The Auditor of State strives to make sure all matters are referred to the agency which has jurisdiction. For this reason, the Auditor of State is referring this matter to the above-mentioned agency.”",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Based on the information provided in the email, the person who sent the story to the attorney general’s office and the auditor’s office has no affiliation with the Turner campaign.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "A representative of the Ohio Ethics Commissions would not confirm or deny any allegations or investigations, noting that under state law, the only investigative documents that are made public are settlement agreements, and no such agreements currently exist on the matter in question.",
